* introduce jthread

false sharing


Acquire locally: later operations cannot move before the load.
Acquire across threads: if the load sees a value stored with release, then prior writes from that thread become visible too.




1. The biggest bottleneck: worker.guard on the hot path

Every local dequeue hits std::lock_guard lock(w.guard) on line 137. Your deque is already lock-free — you're putting a mutex in front of it. The guard exists to protect the steal, but the owner (pop_back) and a thief (steal_front) access opposite ends. You can remove the mutex from the owner's local dequeue entirely — only the steal path needs synchronization with the victim.

2. Random victim selection repeats

dist(rng) on line 69 can pick the same victim multiple times across N attempts. Replace it with a shuffled index array (or just iterate linearly starting from self+1) so you try each worker exactly once.

3. False sharing on Worker

worker.guard and worker.tasks share a cache line with the thread handle. The deque already aligns front/back to 64 bytes internally, but the Worker struct itself isn't aligned. Add alignas(64) to Worker or at minimum to the tasks member.

4. global_guard contention on sleep/wake

The condition variable uses global_guard which is also used by submit. Under load, workers going to sleep contend with submitters. A separate mutex for the condition variable (not shared with the queue) would reduce that.

5. pending_tasks wake condition is coarse

A worker wakes if pending_tasks > 0 but the task may already be claimed by the time it checks. You could track a submitted_since_last_steal counter to make the wakeup more precise, but this is minor.

The biggest win by far is #1 — removing the mutex from the owner's dequeue path is the whole point of a lock-free deque.






False sharing: Yes, still present. front and back are alignas(64) within the deque, but the Worker struct itself has no alignment — so two adjacent workers' heap allocations can share a cache line. Add alignas(64) to Worker.

Other things worth looking at:

Pointer indirection on the hot path — data is a unique_ptr<T[]>, so every push_back/steal_front dereferences a pointer. Since capacity is fixed at 64, an inline T data[64] array would eliminate that. You said deque will be dynamic later so maybe defer this.

Random victim wastes attempts — dist(rng) can pick the same victim multiple times across N tries. Linear wrap starting from self + 1 is simpler and guarantees each worker is tried exactly once.

RNG cost — mt19937 + uniform_int_distribution on every steal attempt is expensive for what it's doing. If you keep random selection, xorshift64 would be much lighter.

steal_count computed after first steal — victim.tasks.size() / 2 is evaluated after you already removed one item, so you're actually stealing slightly less than half. Compute it before the first steal_front.

Spill to global doesn't notify — when push_back returns false and you spill to global queue, there's no condition.notify_one(). A sleeping worker won't wake for it.

The biggest bang right now is alignas(64) on Worker + fixing the victim iteration. Everything else is smaller.


